<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE NATION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A judge in Atlanta dismissed one of 10 perjury counts against former Rep. Pat 
Swindall as the defense began its case. U.S. District Judge Richard C. Freeman 
called the count "just too confusing for a jury trial." The judge also threw 
out more than half an hour of testimony by a defense witness, Rep. Barney Frank 
(D-Mass.) who discussed what knowledge that congressmen do and do not have on 
details of legislation. Swindall is accused of lying to a federal grand jury 
that was investigating the laundering of illegal drug profits. The former 
Republican lawmaker negotiated an $850,000 home loan with a businessman who has 
since been convicted on money laundering charges. The dismissed charge said 
Swindall lied when he testified that he knew little about a mortgage company 
created to funnel the money to Swindall. 
</P>
</TEXT>
