<HEADLINE>
<P>
TENNIS ROUNDUP; 
</P>
<P>
CHANG RANKS NO. 6 AFTER FRENCH WIN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Michael Chang, the Southern California teen-ager whose resolve on center court 
helped him become the first U.S. male since 1955 to win the French Open tennis 
championship, moved to sixth in the world in Monday's Assn. of Tennis 
Professionals computer rankings. 
</P>
<P>
Chang, from Placentia, was ranked No. 19 before the French Open, a clay-court 
tournament in which the 17-year-old upset No. 1-ranked Ivan Lendl in the fourth 
round last Monday after losing the first two sets. Chang defeated Ronald Agenor 
of Haiti in the quarterfinals, Andrei Chesnokov of the Soviet Union in the 
semifinals and Stefan Edberg of Sweden in Sunday's final. 
</P>
<P>
Despite the upset, Lendl remained No. 1, followed by Boris Becker, who lost to 
Edberg in the semifinals at Paris. Edberg remained third, and Andre Agassi was 
No. 4, the highest rated U.S. player. Mats Wilander of Sweden was No. 5, Thomas 
Muster of Austria No. 7, John McEnroe No. 8, Jakob Hlasek of Switzerland No. 9 
and Tim Mayotte No. 10. 
</P>
<P>
Kevin Curren and Mayotte had little trouble defeating fellow Americans to reach 
the second round of the Queen's Club grass-court tournament at London. 
</P>
<P>
Mayotte, seeded fourth, overcame Matt Anger, 6-4, 7-6 (9-7), after saving a set 
point in the tiebreaker. Curren, seeded fifth, outlasted doubles specialist 
Robert Seguso, 6-4, 4-6, 6-2. 
</P>
<P>
While Billie Jean King, Martina Navratilova and Pam Shriver prepared for 
comebacks, 11th-seeded Kathy Rinaldi outlasted Masako Yanagi of Japan, 3-6, 
6-3, 7-5, in a first-round match at a grass-court tournament at Edgbaston, 
England. 
</P>
<P>
Navratilova, ranked second in the world, skipped the clay-court season and will 
begin her Wimbledon preparations this week at Edgbaston, in the suburbs of 
Birmingham. 
</P>
<P>
King, 45, is coming out of a four-year retirement to play doubles and work with 
Navratilova. 
</P>
<P>
Shriver, who has not played singles since April, said she hopes to regain her 
enthusiasm before Wimbledon. 
</P>
<P>
"I needed to take a pause after playing for 10 years," she said. "I don't know 
if my appetite is back, but I spent four hours on court practicing on Sunday." 
</P>
</TEXT>
