<HEADLINE>
<P>
SOUTHLAND; 
</P>
<P>
OC BOARD REJECTS BAN ON AIDS BIAS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Orange County Board of Supervisors, after hearing more than two hours of 
emotionally charged testimony, rejected an ordinance today that would have 
prohibited discrimination against AIDS victims. 
</P>
<P>
The board voted 3-2 against the law, which would have banned discrimination in 
housing, employment, county services or by any business in unincorporated 
county areas because a person has AIDS or tested positive for the HIV virus. 
</P>
<P>
The rejection of the ordinance makes Orange County the only urban county in 
California not to have an AIDS anti-discrimination law on its books. Los 
Angeles, San Diego, San Francisco, Riverside and Alameda counties all have 
enacted similar laws. 
</P>
</TEXT>
