<P>
BID TO FOUL OLD FAITHFUL WATER FAILS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
OLD FAITHFUL, Wyo. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Tests of the vandalized Old Faithful water treatment plant found no 
contamination and visitors to Yellowstone National Park were told they could 
resume drinking the water, a park spokeswoman said today. 
</P>
<P>
An Oregon man who allegedly was caught damaging the plant Sunday was still in 
jail at Mammoth, awaiting transportation to Cheyenne to face a federal criminal 
charge. "He's still not talking so we don't have a motive," park spokeswoman 
Marsha Karle said. "The water was not contaminated so we're turning all the 
drinking fountains back on." 
</P>
<P>
A ranger on routine patrol caught Michael J. Willett, 38, of Sumpter, Ore., 
damaging the equipment used to treat water for the Old Faithful area about 9 
a.m. Sunday, Karle said. The damage was estimated at $10,000 to $25,000 and 
officials decided to ban water consumption in the popular area around Old 
Faithful Geyser in the west-central part of the park. 
</P>
</TEXT>
